Design it like a **producer’s control room**: one screen, multiple lanes, and everything clickable so you can *change* the system, not just watch it. Below is a concrete layout you can build as a local web app or Electron dashboard.

***

## Layout: One Screen, Four Lanes

Think four horizontal “strips” stacked on your laptop screen:

- Lane 1: **Money & Growth**
- Lane 2: **Traffic, Agents, & Quality**
- Lane 3: **Security & Risk**
- Lane 4: **Ops, Outreach, & Build Progress**

Each lane has:
- 2–4 **headline tiles**.
- 1 **interactive control** (dropdown, toggle, slider, or button).
- 1 **detail panel** you can expand.

Dashboards that tie finance, product, and customer metrics drive better decisions than siloed views. [opexengine](https://www.opexengine.com/post/the-top-10-saas-metrics-every-ceo-must-track-for-growth-and-profitability)

***

## Lane 1 – Money & Growth (Top Strip)

Purpose: Show “Is this a business?” and let you *steer* pricing and focus.

Key tiles:

- Live MRR / Usage Revenue
  - Shows:
    - MRR and last 30 days of usage revenue (Middleman + Stripe). [phoenixstrategy](https://www.phoenixstrategy.group/blog/saas-dashboard-design-metrics-ceos-need)
  - Interaction:
    - Click to drill into:
      - By lane (`tap919:` model IDs).
      - By customer segment (agency, ecom, indie).

- Net Revenue Churn / Expansion
  - Shows:
    - 30‑day net revenue churn (%).
    - Expansion vs contraction for existing tenants. [productled](https://www.productled.org/foundations/product-led-growth-metrics)
  - Interaction:
    - Toggle view:
      - “By segment.”
      - “By lane.”

- Top 5 Revenue Lanes
  - Shows:
    - Which `tap919:` models are making the most money:
      - e.g., `tap919:blackmind-lite`, `affiliate:gpt4-mini`.
  - Interaction:
    - Turn each lane on/off for **prominence** in marketing & pricing experiments (writes into a “promote” flag in PricingRule).

Interactive controls:

- **Pricing Experiment Selector**
  - Control:
    - Dropdown with active experiments:
      - “Lane A price up 10%.”
      - “Lane B price down 20%.”
      - “Bundle X vs Bundle Y.”
  - Action:
    - Select experiment → dashboard writes an “experiment config” into DB:
      - Adjusts PricingRule(s).
      - Sets start/end dates.
  - Why:
    - Usage‑based winners run regular, controlled pricing experiments and watch their metrics. [schematichq](https://schematichq.com/blog/why-usage-based-billing-is-taking-over-saas)

***

## Lane 2 – Traffic, Agents, & Quality

Purpose: Show **agent execution health**, volume, and how agents are behaving.

Key tiles:

- Request Volume & Error Rate
  - Shows:
    - Request throughput (per minute/hour) across `/internal/execute` and `/v1/execute`.
    - Error rate with short history. [dotcom-monitor](https://www.dotcom-monitor.com/blog/api-observability-tools/)
  - Interaction:
    - Click to filter by:
      - Tenant.
      - Lane.
      - Region.

- Latency Bands
  - Shows:
    - p50, p95, p99 latency for key endpoints. [levo](https://www.levo.ai/resources/blogs/top-10-api-monitoring-tools-2026)
  - Interaction:
    - Slider to adjust your **SLO target** (e.g., p95 under 800 ms).
    - When you drag the target, agents can:
      - Propose routing changes (e.g., move more traffic to faster provider).

- Active Agents & Failures
  - Shows:
    - Number of active agents (StreetCode + BlackMind) in last 24 hours.
    - Top failing agent workflows (by error count).
  - Interaction:
    - Click an agent → open a side panel that:
      - Offers a `bm.crispr.propose_patch` button to generate a patch plan.

Interactive controls:

- **Routing Mode Switch**
  - Control:
    - Toggle between:
      - “Cheapest route.”
      - “Balanced.”
      - “Fastest route.”
  - Action:
    - Updates a `routing_mode` setting that Middleman Router agent reads and uses to call `tm.routing.score_providers`.
  - Why:
    - API/platform teams use SLOs and routing strategies to juggle cost vs performance; you need the same lever in one click. [blog.cloudflare](https://blog.cloudflare.com/api-gateway/)

***

## Lane 3 – Security & Risk

Purpose: Constantly watch **“Are we safe?”** from abuse, incidents, and compliance.

Key tiles:

- Auth & Key Abuse
  - Shows:
    - Total keys.
    - Keys with anomalous usage (volume spikes, geolocation weirdness).
    - Suspicious IPs or countries.
  - Interaction:
    - Click a key → quick actions:
      - “Lock key.”
      - “Throttle key.”
      - “Flag for investigation.”

- Incident Feed
  - Shows:
    - Stream of:
      - Downtime alerts.
      - Latency SLO breaches.
      - Security anomalies.
    - Color‑coded severity. [dotcom-monitor](https://www.dotcom-monitor.com/blog/api-observability-tools/)
  - Interaction:
    - Click an incident:
      - See related traces (link to OTEL viewer).
      - See “suggested actions” from telemetry agent.

- Compliance/Policy Posture
  - Shows:
    - Simple statuses:
      - “PII handling: OK/warn.”
      - “Data locality: OK/warn.”
  - Interaction:
    - Button to tighten default policies:
      - e.g., “Block US→EU traffic for tenant group X.”

Interactive controls:

- **Threat Level Slider**
  - Control:
    - Slider from:
      - “Relaxed.”
      - “Normal.”
      - “Paranoid.”
  - Action:
    - Adjusts rate limits, anomaly thresholds, and auth strictness:
      - Writes into a `security_profile` table that Middleman and Worker check.
  - Why:
    - API monitoring tools emphasize real‑time detection and anomaly‑based risk; you want a simple, top‑level control instead of manual config editing. [levo](https://www.levo.ai/resources/blogs/top-10-api-monitoring-tools-2026)

***

## Lane 4 – Ops, Outreach, Dev Progress

Purpose: Show how **build, outreach, and support** are moving.

Key tiles:

- Dev Progress & Releases
  - Shows:
    - Number of deployed versions in last 30 days.
    - Next planned release.
    - Key TODO count from GitHub (mapped to your 120‑day roadmap).
  - Interaction:
    - Button to:
      - Trigger a specific deployment (e.g., “Promote staging → prod”).
      - Mark milestones as done (updates a `milestones` table).

- Outreach & Orders
  - Shows:
    - Number of:
      - Active agency conversations.
      - Trial accounts created.
      - Runner signups (affiliates).
  - Interaction:
    - Click each segment:
      - See accounts and last touch.
      - Button: “Assign to Runner” or “Send follow‑up.”

- Runner / Affiliate Panel
  - Shows:
    - Total active Runners.
    - Top 5 by:
      - New tenants.
      - Commission.
  - Interaction:
    - Button: “Boost runner”:
      - Adjusts their commission tier.
      - Generates an updated `tm.affiliate.generate_runner_kit` for them.

Interactive controls:

- **Content Flywheel Control**
  - Control:
    - Two buttons:
      - “Generate morning technical post.”
      - “Generate evening story post.”
  - Action:
    - Calls content agent with:
      - Latest usage trends, successes, and incidents.
      - Produces polished text you can post.
  - Why:
    - Keeping daily content aligned with product metrics is a known PLG tactic; you’re baking it into your dashboard. [productled](https://www.productled.org/foundations/product-led-growth-metrics)

